<article class="techreport">
<title>TEEMSS CCProbe Probe Kit Testing</title>

<para>The following steps should be followed to test a TEEMSS CCProbe
Probe Kit.</para>

<section><title>Contents of a TEEMSS CCProbe Probe Kit</title>

<para>A ProbeKit consists of an interface, probes, and a Palm IIIc
cable for the interface:</para>

<figure><title>TEEMSS CCProbe Probe Kit</title>
<mediaobject>
  <imageobject>
    <imagedata
    fileref="images/jpg/probekit-box-1.jpg" format="JPG"/>
  </imageobject>
</mediaobject>
</figure>

<orderedlist numeration="arabic" spacing="compact">
<listitem><para>interface (including 2 AA batteries)</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>force probe</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>force probe card</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>1 meter cable</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>force probe body</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>smartwheel</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>smartwheel probe card</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>1 meter cable</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>smartwheel body</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>fast response temperature probe</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>current and voltage probe</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>light probe</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>lightprobe probe card</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>1 meter cable</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>light probe sensor card</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>Palm-to-interface cable</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>re-usable shipping and storage box</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>one piece of 1.5" x 2" hook and loop velcro with sticky back</para></listitem>
</orderedlist>

</section>

<section><title>Simple Probe Go/No-Go Testing.</title>

<para>Install the 2 AA batteries.</para>

<para>Test the probes by connecting them to CCProbe running on a Palm connected to the interface.  Open the "CCProbe/Data Collectors" folder.</para>

<orderedlist numeration="arabic" spacing="compact">
<listitem><para>Force Probe</para>
<orderedlist numeration="arabic" inheritnum="inherit" spacing="compact">
<listitem><para> Open the "Force - 20" Data Collector</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Zero the force probe using the Tools menu option "Zero Force Probe"</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Start the data collector again.</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Hang a 1kg weight, force probe response should be 9.8N</para></listitem>
</orderedlist>
</listitem>

<listitem><para>Temperature Probe</para>
<orderedlist numeration="arabic" inheritnum="inherit" spacing="compact">
<listitem><para> make a beaker of water at room temperature</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Measure the temperature of the water</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Open the "Temperature" Data Collector</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Within 5 seconds probe response should be with 1 deg C</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Take temp probe out of water an heat with fingers, temperatture should rise.</para></listitem>
</orderedlist>
</listitem>

<listitem><para>Light Probe</para>
<orderedlist numeration="arabic" inheritnum="inherit" spacing="compact">

<listitem><para> Open the "Light - 4000 Lux" Data Collector</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Open menu Edit:Probe Proerties..</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Set range to dim light and click "OK"</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Start collecting data.</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> place probe 1 foot from 60 watt incandescent bulb</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Values should be 3000 Lux, +/- 500</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> stop collecting data, clear the data</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Open menu Edit:Probe Proerties..</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Set range to bright light and click "OK"</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Start collecting data.</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> place probe 1 foot from 60 watt incandescent bulb</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Values should be 3000 Lux, +/- 500</para></listitem>
</orderedlist>
</listitem>

<listitem><para>Voltgae/Current Probe</para>
  <orderedlist numeration="arabic" inheritnum="inherit" spacing="compact">

  <listitem><para>Test Voltage Measurement</para>
    <orderedlist numeration="arabic" inheritnum="inherit" spacing="compact">
    <listitem><para>Open the "VoltageCurrent - Voltage" Data Collector</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>Open menu Edit:Probe Proerties..</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>Set Speed to "3 per second"</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>Set Version to "2.0"</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>Click "OK"</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>Connect the red and black wires together</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>Measure the voltage, response should be 0 volts, +/- ??</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>Connect red wire to + terminal of 9V battery</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>Connect black wire to - terminal of 9V battery</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>Response should be 9 volts,+/-??</para></listitem>
    </orderedlist>
  </listitem>

<listitem><para>Test Current Measurement</para>
<orderedlist numeration="arabic" inheritnum="inherit" spacing="compact">

<listitem><para>Measure the current, response should be 0 Amps, +/- ??</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>Connect (-) terminal of 9V battery to yellow clip</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>Connect (+) terminal of 9V battery to one lead of 10 Ohm heat cell</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>Connect the other lead of 10 Ohm heat cell to green clip</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>Response should be 0.5 Amps, +/- ??</para></listitem>
</orderedlist>
</listitem>
</orderedlist>
</listitem>

<listitem><para>SmartWheel</para>
<orderedlist numeration="arabic" inheritnum="inherit" spacing="compact">
<listitem><para> Open the "SmartWheel - Velocity" Data Collector</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Connect the SmartWheel</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> Start the data collector.</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> spin the smartwheel clockwize as fast as you can with a quick flip of the wrist</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> you should see a spike to aprox 4m/s and a relatively quick ramp down to 0</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> spin the smartwheel counter-clockwize as fast as you can with a quick flip of the wrist</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> you should see a spike to aprox -4m/s and a relatively quick ramp down to 0</para></listitem>
<listitem><para> there should be no noise spikes in the data larger than 0.1 m/s</para></listitem>
</orderedlist>
</listitem>

</orderedlist>

</section>
